[{"id":39435,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Communication System","question":"","options":["All statements are true","(a), (b) and (c) are true only","(a), (c) and (d) are true only","(b), (c) and (d) are true only"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>For longer wavelength, size of antenna would increase.&nbsp;The size of the antennas should be atleast&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;for high efficiency of signal radiation.&nbsp;</p><p>The effective power radiated by an antenna is inversely proportional to the square of the wavelength, so, for the same antenna length, the power radiated increases with decreasing wavelength or increasing frequency.Hence, the effective power radiated by a long-wavelength baseband signal would be small.</p><p>Also, mixing of signals needs to be avoided, as&nbsp;all the signals get mixed together and a receiver can not separate them from each other.&nbsp;&nbsp;Also, we can use modulation to send low frequency signal by superimposing them with high frequency signals.&nbsp;Electrical audio signals are superimposed on a high frequency wave called the carrier wave. The carrier wave is generated from radio-frequency oscillators and is undamped in nature.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39491,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Communication System","question":"","options":["In frequency modulation the amplitude of the high frequency carrier wave is made to vary in proportion to the amplitude of the audio signal.","In frequency modulation the amplitude of the high frequency carrier wave is made to vary in proportion to the frequency of the audio signal.","In amplitude modulation the amplitude of the high frequency carrier wave is made to vary in proportion to the amplitude of the audio signal.","In amplitude modulation the frequency of the high frequency carrier wave is made to vary in proportion to the amplitude of the audio signal."],"answer":2,"solution":"As per properties of A.M. in amplitude modulation the amplitude of high frequency carrier wave is made to vary in proportion to the amplitude of the audio signal.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (03 Apr)","image":null},{"id":39461,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Communication System","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>B. W. (Bandwidth) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo></math> maximum frequency at modulating signal</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>kHz</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>kHz</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo></math>&nbsp;No of stations accommodate&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>90</mn><mn>10</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>9</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39502,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Communication System","question":"","options":["$80 \\mathrm{~km}$","$16 \\mathrm{~km}$","$40 \\mathrm{~km}$","$64 \\mathrm{~km}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"Maximum distance on earth where object can be detected is $\\mathrm{d}$, then\n$\\begin{array}{ll} \n& (h+R)^2=d^2+R^2 \\\\\n\\Rightarrow & d^2=h^2+2 R h \\\\\n\\text { since } & h < < R, \\quad \\Rightarrow d^2=2 h R \\\\\n\\Rightarrow & d=\\sqrt{2(500)\\left(6.4 \\times 10^6\\right)}=80 \\mathrm{~km}\n\\end{array}$<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/CJx5bNuxeOmXeKmpIErUaSzeDcpis2chmoM5uUIZpU0.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (Offline)","image":null},{"id":39467,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Communication System","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>,</mo><mn>5</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>5</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>8</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>,</mo><mn>8</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>,</mo><mn>5</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>From Given Equation</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#956;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>m</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>&#956;</mi><mi>A</mi><mi>c</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>max</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>min</mi></msub></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>c</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>max</mi></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>min</mi></msub></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math></p><p>From Equation (1) + (2)</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>max</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math></p><p>From Equation (1) &ndash; (2)</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>min</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (02 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39483,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Communication System","question":"","options":["20","10","8","15"],"answer":1,"solution":"Given, modulating frequency $f_m$ $=15 \\mathrm{KHz}$\n$\\therefore \\quad$ Bandwidth of one channel $=2 f_m=30 \\mathrm{kHz}$\n$\\therefore \\quad$ No of channels accommodate\n$$\n=\\frac{300 \\mathrm{kHz}}{30 \\mathrm{kHz}}=10\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 1 Online)","image":null},{"id":39479,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Communication System","question":"","options":["<math><mn>48</mn><mi> </mi><mi>k</mi><mi>m</mi></math>","<math><mn>40</mn><mi> </mi><mi>k</mi><mi>m</mi></math>","<math><mn>80</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>k</mi><mi>m</mi></math>","<math><mn>65</mn><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mi>k</mi><mi>m</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<math><mi>D</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn><msub><mrow><mi>h</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow></msub><mi>R</mi></msqrt><mo>+</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn><msub><mrow><mi>h</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow></msub><mi>R</mi></msqrt></math><br /><br /><math><mi>D</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>140</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>64</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup></msqrt><mo>+</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>40</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>64</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup></msqrt></math><br /><br /><math><mi>D</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>[</mo><msqrt><mn>28</mn></msqrt><mo>+</mo><msqrt><mn>8</mn></msqrt><mo>]</mo></math><br /><br /><math> <mrow>  <mi>D</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#x00D7;</mo><msup>   <mrow>    <mn>10</mn></mrow>   <mn>3</mn>  </msup>  <mrow><mo>[</mo> <mrow>   <mn>2</mn><msqrt>    <mn>7</mn>   </msqrt>   <mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msqrt>    <mn>2</mn>   </msqrt>   </mrow> <mo>]</mo></mrow></mrow></math><br><br /><math> <mrow>  <mi>D</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>16</mn><mo>&#x00D7;</mo><msup>   <mrow>    <mn>10</mn></mrow>   <mn>3</mn>  </msup>  <mrow><mo>[</mo> <mrow>   <msqrt>    <mrow>     <mn>7</mn><mo>+</mo><msqrt>      <mn>2</mn>     </msqrt>     </mrow>   </msqrt>   </mrow> <mo>]</mo></mrow></mrow></math><br><br /><math><mi>D</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>16</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>2.6</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>1.4</mn></mrow></mfenced></math><br /><br /><math><mo>=</mo><mn>64000</mn><mi>m</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>64</mn><mi>k</mi><mi>m</mi><mo>≃</mo><mn>65</mn><mi>k</mi><mi>m</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39399,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Communication System","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi>&#955;</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#955;</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>For efficient radiation and reception, the height of transmitting and receiving antennas should be comparable to a quarter of wavelength of the frequency used. So for efficient transmission of signals of wavelengths<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>&#955;</mi></math>&nbsp;the minimum length of antenna should be&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math>.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (13 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39475,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Communication System","question":"","options":["<math><mn>0.3</mn></math>","<math><mn>0.6</mn></math>","<math><mn>0.4</mn></math>","<math><mn>0.5</mn></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<math><msub><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>100</mn></math><br /><br /><math><msub><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>160</mn></math><br /><br /><math><msub><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>40</mn></math><br /><br /><math><msub><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>,</mo><msub><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>60</mn></math><br /><br /><math><mi>&#956;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>c</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0.6</mn></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39472,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Communication System","question":"","options":["<math><mn>20</mn><mi> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math><mn>51</mn><mi> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math><mn>40</mn><mi> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math><mn>32</mn><mi> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"Range,&nbsp;<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></mrow></msub></msqrt><mo>+</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></mrow></msub></msqrt></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>50</mn><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>6400</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></msub></msqrt><mo>+</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>6400</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>70</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced></msqrt></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>6400</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></msub></msqrt><mo>=</mo><mn>50</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>8</mn><msqrt><mn>14</mn></msqrt></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msup><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>50</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>8</mn><msqrt><mn>14</mn></msqrt></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>6400</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0.031458</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math><br /><math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></mrow></msub><mo>&#8776;</mo><mn>32</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39404,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Communication System","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>MHz</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>kHz</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>MHz</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>kHz</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The relation between bandwidth and the signal frequency is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Bandwidth</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>signal</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>frequency</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>Substitute the values of the known parameter into equation (1) to calculate the required bandwidth.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnalign=\"right center left\" columnspacing=\"0px\"><mtr><mtd><mi>Bandwidth</mi></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>kHz</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>kHz</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (10 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39436,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Communication System","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Here,&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>h</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>49</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>h</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>25</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>64</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>5</mn></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p><p>Maximum distance between two antennae is,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>d</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mi>R</mi><msub><mi>h</mi><mi>T</mi></msub></msqrt><mo>+</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mi>R</mi><msub><mi>h</mi><mi>R</mi></msub></msqrt><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mi>R</mi><mfenced><mn>49</mn></mfenced></msqrt><mo>+</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mi>R</mi><mfenced><mn>25</mn></mfenced></msqrt><mo>=</mo><mn>12</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mi>R</mi></msqrt><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mn>12</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>64</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>5</mn></msup></msqrt><mo>=</mo><mn>192</mn><msqrt><mn>5</mn></msqrt><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/936c12b7-f2a1-4671-b6a7-a1b10c507f4f-image.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 91px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39417,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Communication System","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>32</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>km</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>28</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>km</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>36</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>km</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>64</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>km</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Given:&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p><p>Using the relation between the range of the radio communication and the height of the transmission antenna&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>h</mi><mi>T</mi></msub></math> and the receiving antenna&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>h</mi><mi>R</mi></msub></math>, the maximum line of sight distance between two antennas, is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>d</mi><mi>max</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mi>R</mi><msub><mi>h</mi><mi>T</mi></msub></msqrt><mo>+</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mi>R</mi><msub><mi>h</mi><mi>R</mi></msub></msqrt></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>d</mi><mi>max</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>80</mn></msqrt><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mo>=</mo><mn>64000</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mo>=</mo><mn>64</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>km</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39401,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Communication System","question":"","options":["A and B only","A and C only","A and D only","A, D and E only"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>The carrier wave frequency is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnalign=\"right center left\" columnspacing=\"0px\"><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>f</mi><mi>c</mi></msub></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><mrow><mn>1000</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>500</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Hz</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p><p>The modulating&nbsp;wave frequency is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnalign=\"right center left\" columnspacing=\"0px\"><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>f</mi><mi>m</mi></msub></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Hz</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p><p>Hence, the frequencies contained in the modulated signal are given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnspacing=\"0px\" columnalign=\"right center left\"><mtr><mtd><mi>f</mi></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><msub><mi>f</mi><mi>c</mi></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>f</mi><mi>m</mi></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>f</mi><mi>m</mi></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>f</mi><mi>c</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>f</mi><mi>m</mi></msub></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd/><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>498</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Hz</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>500</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Hz</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>502</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Hz</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (12 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39413,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Communication System","question":"","options":["A only","A, D and E only","B only","A and B only"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>The frequency components of amplitude modulated signal are&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>f</mi><mi>c</mi></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>f</mi><mi>m</mi></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>f</mi><mi>c</mi></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>f</mi><mi>c</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>f</mi><mi>m</mi></msub></math></p><p>Here, carrier wave frequency is</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>f</mi><mi>c</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>100</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>500</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Hz</mi></math></p><p>Modulating wave frequency is&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>f</mi><mi>m</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Hz</mi></math></p><p>So, the frequencies in amplitude modulated signal are <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>498</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Hz</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>500</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Hz</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>502</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Hz</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (31 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39489,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Communication System","question":"","options":["<math><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>c</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>200</mn><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mi>H</mi><mi>z</mi><mo>;</mo><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mi>&nbsp;</mi><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>50</mn><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mi>H</mi><mi>z</mi><mo>;&nbsp;</mo><mi>μ</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>c</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>150</mn><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mi>H</mi><mi>z</mi><mo>;</mo><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>50</mn><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mi>H</mi><mi>z</mi><mo>;&nbsp;</mo><mi>μ</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>c</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>150</mn><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mi>H</mi><mi>z</mi><mo>;</mo><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>30</mn><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mi>H</mi><mi>z</mi><mo>;&nbsp;</mo><mi>μ</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>c</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>200</mn><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mi>H</mi><mi>z</mi><mo>;</mo><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>30</mn><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mi>H</mi><mi>z</mi><mo>;&nbsp;</mo><mi>μ</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"Compare with<br /><br /><math> <mrow> <msub> <mi>C</mi> <mi>m</mi> </msub> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><msub> <mi>A</mi> <mi>c</mi> </msub> <mi>sin</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><msub> <mi>w</mi> <mi>c</mi> </msub> <mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>+</mo><mfrac> <mrow> <mi>μ</mi><msub> <mi>A</mi> <mi>c</mi> </msub> </mrow> <mn>2</mn> </mfrac> <mrow><mo>[</mo> <mrow> <mi>cos</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><msub> <mi>w</mi> <mi>c</mi> </msub> <mo>−</mo><msub> <mi>w</mi> <mi>m</mi> </msub> <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>−</mo><mi>cos</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><msub> <mi>w</mi> <mi>c</mi> </msub> <mo>+</mo><msub> <mi>w</mi> <mi>m</mi> </msub> <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo> </mrow> <mo>]</mo></mrow> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mfrac> <mrow> <mi>μ</mi><msub> <mi>A</mi> <mi>c</mi> </msub> </mrow> <mn>2</mn> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <msub> <mi>A</mi> <mi>c</mi> </msub> <mo>=</mo><mn>30</mn></math><br /><br /><math> <mi>μ</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac> <mn>2</mn> <mn>3</mn> </mfrac> </math><br /><br /><math> <msub> <mi>w</mi> <mi>c</mi> </msub> <mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>π</mi><msub> <mi>f</mi> <mi>c</mi> </msub> <mo>=</mo><mn>300</mn><mi>π</mi> </math><math> <mo>⇒</mo><msub> <mi>f</mi> <mi>c</mi> </msub> <mo>=</mo><mn>150</mn><mi>H</mi><mi>z</mi> </math><br /><br /><math> <msub> <mi>w</mi> <mi>c</mi> </msub> <mo>−</mo><msub> <mi>w</mi> <mi>m</mi> </msub> <mo>=</mo><mn>200</mn><mi>π</mi> </math><br /><br /><math> <msub> <mi>w</mi> <mi>m</mi> </msub> <mo>=</mo><mn>100</mn><mi>π</mi> </math><br /><br /><math> <msub> <mi>f</mi> <mi>m</mi> </msub> <mo>=</mo><mn>50</mn><mi>H</mi><mi>z</mi> </math><br /><br />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (10 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":39488,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Communication System","question":"","options":["<math><msub><mrow><mi>&#969;</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>c</mi></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mrow><mi>&#969;</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></msub></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mi>&#969;</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></msub></math><br />&nbsp;","<math><msub><mrow><mi>&#969;</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>c</mi></mrow></msub></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mi>&#969;</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mrow><mi>&#969;</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>c</mi></mrow></msub></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<math><mo>&#8757;</mo></math>&nbsp;<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#916;</mi><msub><mrow><mi>&#969;</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></msub><mo>&#8810;</mo><msub><mrow><mi>&#969;</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>c</mi></mrow></msub></math><br /><br /><math><msub><mrow><mi>&#969;</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></msub></math> will not be there in the frequencies.<br /><br />In modulated wave<br /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f101a752-fa67-4593-8ce7-977cbb0f2b87-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 142px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (02 Apr)","image":null},{"id":39428,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Communication System","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>20</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>30</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>50</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Given: Frequency <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mi>MHz</mi></math></p><p>Frequency <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mi>MHz</mi></math></p><p>Wavelength can be calculated using&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#955;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>c</mi><mi>f</mi></mfrac></math>.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>c</mi><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>8</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>50</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>c</mi><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>8</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>10</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>30</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p><p>Wavelength bandwidth is the difference of upper lower wavelengths&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39450,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Communication System","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>max</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"italic\">c</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"italic\">m</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>12</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>min</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>c</mi></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>m</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"italic\">c</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>15</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mrow><mo mathvariant=\"italic\">&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"italic\">A</mi></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"italic\">m</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>9</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></p><p>Modulation index <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"italic\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"italic\">m</mi></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"italic\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"italic\">c</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>9</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mstyle><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>15</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mstyle></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39497,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Communication System","question":"","options":["Ground wave signals are more stable than the sky wave signals.","The critical frequency of an ionospheric layer is the highest frequency that will be reflected back by the layer when it is vertically incident.","Electromagnetic waves of frequencies higher than about $30 \\mathrm{MHz}$ cannot penetrate the ionosphere.","Sky wave signals in the broadcast frequency range are stronger at night than in the day time."],"answer":2,"solution":"Above critical frequency $\\left(f_c\\right)$, an electromagnetic wave penetrates the ionosphere and is not reflected by it.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (23 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":39451,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Communication System","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>In radio communications, a sideband is a band of frequencies higher than or lower than the carrier frequency, that are the result of the modulation process.&nbsp;The signal components&nbsp;above the carrier frequency constitute the upper sideband (USB), and those below the carrier frequency constitute the lower sideband (LSB).</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/119962ca-b8fa-4e54-ad91-801d290270cc-image.png\" style=\"width: 304px; height: 188px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>a</mi><mn>10</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>b</mi><mn>10</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>&#956;</mi><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>C</mi></msub></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mi>a</mi><mi>b</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39499,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Communication System","question":"","options":["$\\omega_c$ and $\\sqrt{\\omega_c^2+\\omega_m^2}$","$\\omega_c, \\omega_c+\\omega_m$ and $\\omega_c-\\omega_m$","$\\omega_c$ and $\\omega_m$","$\\omega_c$ and $\\sqrt{\\omega_c \\omega_m}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"The frequencies present in amplitude modulated wave are :\nCarrier frequency $=\\omega_c$\nUpper side band frequency $=\\omega_c+\\omega_m$\nLower side band frequency $=\\omega_c-\\omega_m$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (19 May Online)","image":null},{"id":39463,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Communication System","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>c</mi><mrow><msub><mi>f</mi><mi>c</mi></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>f</mi><mi>m</mi></msub></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>c</mi><msub><mi>f</mi><mi>m</mi></msub></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>c</mi><msub><mi>f</mi><mi>c</mi></msub></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>c</mi><mrow><msub><mi>f</mi><mi>c</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>f</mi><mi>m</mi></msub></mrow></mfrac></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"Given frequency of massage signal <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>f</mi><mi>m</mi></msub></math> frequency of carrier signal <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>f</mi><mi>c</mi></msub></math><br />the wavelength of the corresponding signal in air is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>&#955;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>c</mi><msub><mi>f</mi><mi>c</mi></msub></mfrac></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39425,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Communication System","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Given here,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>C</mi><mfenced><mi>t</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mi>sin</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>8</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo></math>volts.</p><p>From&nbsp;the carrier wave equation we have,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>C</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></math>&nbsp;and from the graph we have,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>m</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>.</p><p>Modulation Index <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#956;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>m</mi></msub><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>C</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>5</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn></math></p><p>Where,&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>m</mi></msub><mo>=</mo></math> amplitude&nbsp;of modulating signal</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>c</mi></msub><mo>=</mo></math> amplitude&nbsp;of carrier wave</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39443,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Communication System","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"The value of maximum amplitude,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>max</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>c</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>m</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>250</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>150</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>400</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math><br />, and the value of minimum amplitude,<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>min</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>c</mi></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>m</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>250</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>150</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>min</mi></msub><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>max</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>100</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>400</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>50</mn><mn>200</mn></mfrac></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>200</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (01 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39465,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Communication System","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Sound level decreases by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>dB</mi></math> every <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>km</mi></math> so, sound level decreased in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>20</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>km</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>dB</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#946;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>&#946;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>log</mi><mn>10</mn></msub><mfrac><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>log</mi><mn>10</mn></msub><mfrac><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>10</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></msup><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></msup><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>W</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (24 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39423,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Communication System","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>220</mn><mi>kHz</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>180</mn><mi>kHz</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>360</mn><mi>kHz</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>440</mn><mi>kHz</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Given</p><p>FM broadcast</p><p>Modulating frequency <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>kHz</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>f</mi></math></p><p>Deviation ratio <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>frequency</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>deviation</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>modulating</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>frequency</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>&#8710;</mo><mi>f</mi></mrow><mi>f</mi></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo></math> Frequency deviation,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#916;</mi><mi>f</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>f</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>10</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>kHz</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>200</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>kHz</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo></math> Bandwidth <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mfenced><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>&#916;</mi><mi>f</mi></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mfenced><mrow><mn>20</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>200</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>kHz</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>440</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>kHz</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39480,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Communication System","question":"","options":["<math><mn>6.25</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math><mn>4.87</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math><mn>3.75</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math><mn>3.86</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"Available signal width <math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>100</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>c</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>λ</mi></mrow></mfrac></math> <br/><br/> <math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>100</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>8</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>800</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mi> </mi><mi>H</mi><mi>z</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3.75</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>12</mn></mrow></msup><mi> </mi><mi>H</mi><mi>z</mi></math> <br/><br/>Number of available channels <math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3.75</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>12</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></math> <br/><br/> <math><mo>=</mo><mn>6.25</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39485,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Communication System","question":"","options":["<math><mn>2</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math><mn>2</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math><mn>2</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math><mn>2</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"Number of telephonic channels that can be transmitted simultaneously,&nbsp;<br /><br /><math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0.1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (08 Apr)","image":null},{"id":39421,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Communication System","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Frequencies present in output of square law device</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>f</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>f</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>f</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>f</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>f</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>f</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>f</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>f</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></msub></math></p><p>After passing through band pass filter, frequencies present&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>f</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>f</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>f</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>f</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>f</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></msub></math></p><p>Bandwidth of the output signal <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>f</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>&#969;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></msub></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>28</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>14</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>MHz</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jul Shift 2)","image":null}]